<br>
And remember that &quot;cheating&quot; and &quot;exploiting&quot; are verbs.  &quot;Exploiting&quot; would be when a player cheats using an exploit. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nicolheartsbane>Nicol Heartsbane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 946<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/1/03 11:59:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25564.topic&index=110>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.hiwaay.net/~kostrom/erudite.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Define &quot;exploit&quot;</span><hr size=1> On cases e,f,g,i,j Goladus identifies instances of regular play as &quot;exploits&quot; using his definition, or at least leans towards that conclusion.  In my opinion, all of these are cases where someone has an unfair advantage as a result of something other than cheating.  If you are playing the game fairly, but you have better friends, better gear, or are on the good side of a poor verant balancing decision, you are not cheating.  <br>
<br>
My previous claim went unchallenged, so I assume we all agree that the point of this is to determine what actions are &quot;cheats&quot; when we try to determine what is an exploit.<br>
<br>
[quote]<br>
i) Using high level equipment on a low level character.<br>
<br>
Not an exploit unless you are twinking. If you are twinking it is an exploit. However there are limits now to prevent the most extreme cases of this, and in my experience the advantages aren't quite as big as people seem to think. In any case it is a very non-serious exploit.<br>
[/quote]<br>
<br>
Let's consider two warriors.  <br>
<br>
Hanz is a level 20 barbarian.  He has worked hard for his banded armor, +2 agility earrings, and he has completed a langsaxe quest and purchased a centi shortsword.  He's doing okay, when he can get a healer and maybe a few others to group up, and they tear up mammoths, or smething.<br>
<br>
Franz is a level 20 barbarian.  He wears a fungi tunic, RBB haste, he has some awesome weapons which I forget the name of, and a stack of crimson potions.  He started his character recently, and is passing through on his way to solo in permafrost.<br>
<br>
Franz has an unfair advantage; he met this chick at the DQ who is really cute and when she heard he played eq, she set him up so they can play together, as soon as he levels up some.  He has better gear.  He intends to use it.  The developers never intended for a level 20 warrior to have that gear.<br>
<br>
check, check, check - definition matches - definition is wrong.<br>
<br>
Franz is not CHEATING.  Okay, so he has better friends than you do, that's not fair, tough.  EQ and life are simply not fair.  Unfair is not the same as cheating, and the whole point of the discussion was to define what is cheating.  It seems that the &quot;unfair&quot; test in the definition is failing us, here.<br>
<br>
I hope we all can agree that if an act of playing by the rules is never an exploit, in the sense of the word that we are trying to define.<br>
<br>
(ps: All those &quot;the act of&quot; phrases are in there to please Goladus's grammatical sensibilities, and to make clear what I mean when I freely interchange the noun and verb.)<br>
<br>
(pps: I have proposed measures that would balance the playing field between Hanz and Franz, but I would never agree that Franz is cheating, nor would I consider it acceptable to start banning people who twink.)<br>
