<br>
check, check, check - definition matches - definition is wrong.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Here is the problem:<br>
<br>
Based on your explanation of the scenario, Franz IS exploiting and the definition is right.  Why?  Because you describe the advantage as unfair.  Just because someone has an advantage doesn't make it an unfair advantage.  Having friends is not in itself an unfair advantage, having friends that give you gear is not something that was unintended.  However being able to equip yourself with high level gear at a low level is also not intended.  So how is this dealt with?<br>
<br>
1.  Abilities are limited by level.  A hill giant will smush a level 20 twink almost as fast as he'd squish a level 20 non-twink, because defense skill is limited.<br>
<br>
2.  Most of the really powerful items now have recommended or required levels on them, preventing their use at lower levels.  Thus one can suggest that items that are currently not restricted do not generally grant an unfair advantage.  Any advantage gained through twinking is a fair advantage.  Personally I think giving equipment to alts is a mild exploit, but most other means of obtaining high level equipment at low levels is an intended part of the game... to an extent, an extent which is enforced with in-game rules.  The Fungi Tunic is probably the most extreme example.  At worst, it's a grandfathered item that really should have a required level on it, but they don't add because they're not totally evil.<br>
<br>
The difference between high level buffs and item twinking is that the level restriction on items works.  The restriction on buffs does not. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nicolheartsbane>Nicol Heartsbane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 949<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/1/03 10:28:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25564.topic&index=116>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.hiwaay.net/~kostrom/erudite.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Define &quot;exploit&quot;</span><hr size=1> Goladus: &quot;Based on your explanation of the scenario, Franz IS exploiting and the definition is right. Why? Because ...&quot;  and here you describe how it is an unintended and unfair advantage, which is how we tentatively defined it.<br>
<br>
Dude ... we postulated a tentative definition and now we're examining whether the definition works, or at least that was what I was doing all along.  It comes up with the wrong conclusion; consequently, it does not work.  You cannot say &quot;Oh, but the definition is right because it says that is an exploit, and it is according to the definition!&quot;  That is circular logic.  I already covered showing that the definition says that is an exploit, so you don't have to go through that again.  The problem is that it is not, therefore the definition is wrong.<br>
<br>
The point I just made is that your working definition would support the banning of any players who benefit from poor balancing decisions on the part of Verant staff.  It must be modified to account for the difference between cheating and not cheating.  If you can't make these small adjustments when the definition is shown to be in error, then ... I guess you will keep repeating the same mistakes.<br>
<br>
The actual line from the rules of conduct does account for this important distinction:<br>
<br>
12. You will not exploit any bug in EverQuest and you will not communicate the existence of any such exploitable bug (bugs that grant the user unnatural or unintended benefits in game), either directly or through public posting, to any other user of EverQuest. You will promptly report any such bug via the in-game &quot;/bug&quot; command or via the eqtesting@soe.sony.com email address.<br>
<br>
Our use of &quot;exploit&quot; is slang shorthand for, as Verant puts it, exploiting a bug for unnatural or unintended benefits.  As stated there, 'exploit' is a simple English word, correctly used, which means &quot;to take advantage of,&quot; with pejorative connotation.  Obviously, this says &quot;DON'T CHEAT.&quot;  <br>
<br>
If we come up with a definition of exploit that differs, then either it is WRONG or you are making up words for something completely off topic and irrelevant, and you might as well call it gimboling, in honor of Lewis Caroll.<br>
<br>
You are gimboling if you purposefully arrange to benefit from an unintended situation!  I'm sure we can all agree that gimbolers will reach higher levels faster without ever learning how to play skillfully, and I would hesitate to group with them;  However, they're not going to get their accounts suspended for gimboling, because neither the EULA nor the rules of conduct place any prohibitions against gimboling.<br>
<br>
Of course, we all want Verant to take actions to maintain game balance, but a point I must stick to is that game balance discussions are not the same as discussions about cheating/exploiting, even if they may overlap in specific cases.<br>
<br>
<br>
