<br>
Rather than having a spell check it's recipient, it checks it's target.  On a single target spell, this is the same thing, but on a group spell, it needs to be treated as 6 buffs being cast at once.  It should bounce off those not of the correct level, and stick to those that are.<br>
<br>
Basically, the check should happen when it tries to go into your buff box, not when you try to cast it.  Currently the logic says &quot;ok, target is greater than 45, allow the cast&quot;.  Better logic would say &quot;Ok, I'm trying to recieve a buff that's too high, reject it.&quot;<br>
<br>
While many of you may hate Anarchy Online, their spell (nano) system rocks.<br>
--You must have sufficent skill (not level) to cast most spells.<br>
--You can buff your casting skills and thereby use more powerfull spells.<br>
--Buffs take up storage space on the character, Higher level buffs take more of this space.  Gear, which requires skill level to equip, can modify how much of this storage space you have.<br>
--Buff partical effects are persistant... every few seconds a buff is chosen randomly, and the effect for it is displayed.  My personal pet peeve in EQ is that I should be able to tell before I hit something that it's bristling with spikes or covered in flames....<br>
--Buffs look at the recipient. If one person lacks the NCU or in a few cases level for a group buff, it bounces off that person, and sticks to everyone else<br>
<br>
<br>
I hope Sony is paying attention to it's competition as it develops EQ 2.  DAOC and AO in particular have a great many gameplay features that blow EQ away.  One thing I love about AO, I must mention in passing... Their pet pathing made EQ's look pristine and logical, in a recent patch they actually fixed it.  They didn't do this with a crappy spell like Summon Companion or making it warp or something else equally hackish... they fixed it with AI.  If a pet encounters an obstacle in it's path, it attempts to JUMP over it, and if that don't work, it goes AROUND it, OMG OMG....  It's thinking like this that will, with some polishing on their network code and a few other tweaks, send companies like Funcom to the top over Sony if Sony continues in the same vein that it has shown with EQ.<br>
