<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It comes up with the wrong conclusion; consequently, it does not work.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->The definition did not come to the wrong conclusion, you did not use the definition properly.  Sorry to be harsh, but that is my argument.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You cannot say &quot;Oh, but the definition is right because it says that is an exploit, and it is according to the definition!&quot; That is circular logic. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->It is not circular logic, it depends on an opinion that is all.  But there are two different opinions:<br>
<br>
1.  Unfair advantage<br>
2.  Unintended glitch in the game.<br>
<br>
Both have to be true for it to be an exploit.  I will agree that a third point:  That the player is cheating, is necessary if you are defining the term exploit as a verb.<br>
<br>
Whether or not something is an unfair advantage will no doubt be disputed, and thus whether or not something is an exploit will be disputed too.  However, the definition helps us to break a situation it down into simpler components and analyze each one individually.  Instead of arguing broadly about whether or not is an exploit, we can break it down into an argument about whether or not it is unfair and unintended.<br>
<br>
There is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>some</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> relationship between unfair and unintended, but I believe it is indirect enough so as not to be &quot;circular logic.&quot;  The game will never be totally fair, and they &quot;intend&quot; a ceritan degree of unfairness.  However I don't think it's reasonable to think that they intend &quot;incredible&quot; or &quot;gross&quot; unfairness, and any situation that can successfully be argued as grossly unfair will also likely suggest that the situation was also not intended and is thus an exploit.  In contrast an extreme, unintended bug won't necessarily be unfair. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=artillis>Artillis</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<BR>Enjoys Sheep Erotica</span><br>  Posts: 1709<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/2/03 1:56:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25564.topic&index=119>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Define &quot;exploit&quot;</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Based on your explanation of the scenario, Franz IS exploiting and the definition is right. Why? Because you describe the advantage as unfair.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
